<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-340-381  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 340 381.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Feb 6 1989 v216 n6 p36(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>But can they sell it? Three analysts look at telephoneparticipation in the information age. (Maria Lewis, MichaelKennedy, Francis McInerney) (panel discussion)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis; Wilson, Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telephony magazine invited three of the telecommunicationsindustry's most articulate analysts - Maria Lewis from ShearsonLehman Hutton Inc; Michael Kennedy from Arthur D. Little Inc; andFrancis McInerney from Northern Business Information - to discuss,among other topics, the issue of enhanced public network services.andO;All three analyst responded negatively to whether or not telephonecompanies could sell advanced services, saying that thesecompanies still have much to learn about marketing andsalesmanship.andP;  But one analyst noted that these companies are veryaware of their shortcomings and are working hard to address theproblem by rethinking their strategies or acquiring niche playerswith well-established track records.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Industry AnalystsTelecommunicationsMarketing StrategyForecastingTelephone systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Maria Lewis, Michael Kennedy, Francis McInerney. (portrait)Person:    Lewis, Maria (attitudes); Kennedy, Michael (attitudes); McInerney,Francis (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>